VI don't have a problem, actually,
p271
aVwith Donald Trump's credo of "America first."
p272
aVIt seems to me that that's a pretty banal statement
p273
aVof what politicians have always done and probably should always do.
p274
aVOf course they're elected to represent the interests of their own people.
p275
aVBut what I find so boring and so old-fashioned
p276
aVand so unimaginative about his take on that
p277
aVis that America first means everyone else last,
p278
aVthat making America great again means making everybody else small again,
p279
aVand it's just not true.
p280
aVIn my job as a policy advisor over the last 20 years or so,
p281
aVI've seen so many hundreds of examples of policies
p282
aVthat harmonize the international and the domestic needs,
p283
aVand they make better policy.
p284
aVI'm not asking nations to be altruistic or self-sacrificing.
p285
aVThat would be ridiculous.
p286
aVNo nation would ever do that.
p287
aVI'm asking them to wake up and understand that we need a new form of governance,
p288
aVwhich is possible
p289
aVand which harmonizes those two needs,
p290
aVthose good for our own people and those good for everybody else.
p291
aVSince the US election and since Brexit
p292
aVit's become more and more obvious to me
p293
aVthat those old distinctions of left wing and right wing
p294
aVno longer make sense.
p295
aVThey really don't fit the pattern.
p296
aVWhat does seem to matter today
p297
aVis very simple,
p298
aVwhether your view of the world is
p299
aVthat you take comfort from looking inwards and backwards,
p300
aVor whether, like me, you find hope in looking forwards and outwards.
p301
aVThat's the new politics.
p302
aVThat's the new division that is splitting the world right down the middle.
p303
aVNow, that may sound judgmental, but it's not meant to be.
